  "why": "The paper applies image-space transformations (rotation, translation, shear, zoom, brightness, contrast) with explicit parameter ranges and validates transformation parameters (isValid) and applies transformations on the original image in-memory via a Keras data generator. These operations are generally less sensitive to serialization-induced precision loss than very small, in-memory floating perturbations (e.g., sub-pixel float noise), so many fault-inducing variants are likely to survive typical image serialization. However, the paper does not explicitly describe enforcing input-format serialization constraints (e.g., clipping to [0,255], rounding to integer pixel precision, or steps taken to ensure perturbations survive conversion from normalized float representations back to serialized image formats). Because there is no explicit handling of rounding/clipping or discussion of failure reproducibility after serialization, the approach matches the “Medium” level: uses transformations less sensitive to serialization but does not explicitly enforce all input-format constraints.",
